@node Licence "ExChanger - Licence agreement"

	@{fg shine}@{b}Disclaimer@{ub}@{fg text}

	@{b}THIS SOFTWARE IS PROVIDED "AS IS" WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY OF ANY KIND, EITHER EXPRESS OR IMPLIED. THE ENTIRE RISK AS TO THE USE OF THIS SOFTWARE IS ASSUMED BY THE USER.@{ub}

	
	@{fg shine}@{b}Important@{ub}@{fg text}

	This software is not a program, and even less a compressor. This software is a simple AMIGADos script that makes several things in one go, making the whole process easier. ExChanger doesn't make the archives smaller, Lzx does. Lzx is the program responsible for the greater compression rate. ExChanger only does in a more easier way what you could do (type) using the shell. All the hard work is done by the programs Lzx, Lha, UnZip and Zoo (compression/decompression), ExChanger only feeds the necessary information to them and acts as an interface between you, the user, and those programs.

	@{fg shine}@{b}Copyright and legal matters@{ub}@{fg text}

	This script is released under the concept of GIFTWARE. The script, docs and all the files are copyright to me but you may use them for as long as you like. I only ask you to report any bugs or to send me any suggestions. If you like this script and think that the author should get something for his effort then you can send me a gift. And, what do I mean by a gift? A gift can be a disk with your own material (pics, anims, progs,...), a disk with PD or ShareWare, or simply a postcard or letter. I don't ask for much, I simply ask you to contact me. Even if you don't like it, contact me anyway. I will appreciate any comments you send me.

	@{fg shine}@{b}Distribution@{ub}@{fg text}

	If you want to distribute the ExChanger script you may do so as long as you include @{u}all the files@{uu} and don't ask @{u}any money@{uu} for it.
@endnode

@node Intro "ExChanger - Introduction"

	@{fg shine}@{b}Hello!@{ub}@{fg text}

	This script is my first contribution to the AMIGA community.
	I hope you find it useful.

	@{fg shine}@{b}And, now the script.@{ub}@{fg text}

	Exchanger is a little AMIGADos script with the main purpose of making easier the conversion of Lha/Zip/Zoo archives to Lzx ones.
	As you surely know Lzx is the most efficient archiver for the AMIGA. But, most of the archives we see on AMINet, CD-Roms, etc, are in Lha/Lzh format. So, to make these archives smaller you need to convert them to Lzx ones. In the other hand, if you get an archive from a PC it will most probably be in Zip format. It makes sense to convert it to a LZX archive because it will be smaller and then the archive will be in a format native to the AMIGA. To do all these conversions you will need a good knowledge of the shell and a great reserve of patience, or you may use ExChanger and do all the conversions easily. ExChanger converts Lha/Lzh/Zip/Zoo archives to Lzx ones using the Lha, UnZip, Zoo and Lzx programs. ExChanger dearchives the files to a temporary directory using Lha, UnZip or Zoo and then archives them back into a new archive using Lzx. This process can reduce the size of the archive severally.

	@{fg shine}@{b}A practical case.@{ub}@{fg text}

	You have just downloaded an archive (.Lha/Lzh, .Zip or .Zoo) from AMINet containing a great utility (like ExChanger) and you want to keep the archive and send it to a friend using a modem (ExChanger is so good that your friend must have it). In either case it makes sense reducing the file's length. It will use less storage space and reduce the phone bill. Then, you should use Lzx to reduce the file's length and ExChanger is here to help you do that.
@endnode

@node Sys "ExChanger - System requirements"

	@{fg shine}@{b}Hardware@{ub}@{fg text}

	Any AMIGA will do the job.


	@{fg shine}@{b}Software@{ub}@{fg text}

	You need the following programs in your c: directory:

	@{b}@{"Lzx" link Coprigt 1}   © 1995 Data Compression Technologies

	@{"Lha" link Coprigt 9}   © 1991,92 Stefan Boberg
	@{"UnZip" link Coprigt 17} By Info-ZIP.
	       Portions © 1989 S. H. Smith
	       AMIGA: John Rush
	              Paul Kienitz
	@{"Zoo" link Coprigt 29}   © Rahul Dhesi
	       AMIGA: J. Brian Waters@{ub}

	Note: Make sure you install the version of Lzx that most suits your AMIGA's processor. This way Lzx will take the most of your AMIGA's setup. For more information read the Lzx documentation.

	And the following AMIGADos commands:

	Cd		Copy		Delete
	Dir		Echo		Else
	EndIf		Eval		If
	Lab		List		Makedir
	Quit		RequestChoice	RequestFile
	Set		Skip		UnSet
	Wait

	Most of these commands are with AMIGADos since Wb 1.3 but some of them are only Wb 2.1+ or Wb 3+. So, I can only say that the ExChanger program will work on a 3.0 system and will not on a 1.3 system (mainly due to the GUI part of the program). It could work on a 2.04, 2.05 or 2.1 system with the addition of the missing commands. But, I don't know.
@endnode

@node Install "ExChanger - Installation"

	@{fg shine}@{b}Installing Exchanger.@{ub}@{fg text}

	To install ExChanger you should copy all the files to a directory of your choice:

	@{b}The files are:@{ub}

	ExChanger
	ExChanger.Info
	ExFileInDirOrig
	ExFileOutDirOrig
	ExTempDirOrig
	ExLzxTestOrig
	Documentation (folder)
	Documentation.info

	@{b}Note:@{ub} You should not install ExChanger in the root directory of a disk (Ex: DF0:, Work:, Ram:) because ExChanger will not recognize your personal settings (@{i}ExTempDirOrig@{ui}, @{i}ExFileInDirOrig@{ui}, @{i}ExFileOutDirOrig@{ui} and @{i}ExLzxTestOrig@{ui}). The script will work but with its internal settings.

	Internal settings:

	   Temporary Directory:   Ram:ExChangerDir/
	   File  In  Directory:   DF0:
	   File  Out Directory:   DF0:
	   Testing flag:          No


	@{fg shine}@{b}Changing the initial settings.@{ub}@{fg text}

	To change ExChanger settings you may choose to take one of two different way:

	@{b}From the outside:@{ub}

	To change the @{b}temporary@{ub} and @{b}files@{ub} directories you will need to edit the correspondent files (using Ed or any other text editor).

	To change the @{b}temporary@{ub} directory you will need to edit the file@{i} ExTempDirOrig@{ui}. Use Ed (AMIGADos command) or a text editor and change the directory listed in the file to your own.
	Example:
	Work:ExChanger/GreatScript/TemporaryDir
	Now save the file.

	There are two major things to remember:
	1st - Save the file with the original name @{i}ExTempDirOrig@{ui} and place it in the directory containing the ExChanger program.
	2nd - The directory that you choose to use as the @{b}temporary@{ub} directory must be @{fg shine}@{b}empty@{fg text}@{ub} because if it isn't you will loose all the files in it. ExChanger will delete them.

	To change the @{b}files@{ub}' directories you need to edit the files @{i}ExFileInDirOrig@{ui} and @{i}ExFileOutDirOrig@{ui}. These directories are where ExChanger looks for the archives to convert (In) and where to save the final archive (Out). You can assign these directories to where you like, it's not necessary that these directories contain archives. These options are only important when you start ExChanger because after a conversion, ExChanger remembers the directories where it loaded the Lha/Zip/Zoo archive and where it saved the Lzx archive. So, if you have 20 archives to convert in A:B/C/..../Z directory there is no need to browse through the A: disk until you reach the subdirectory z every time you want to select an archive to convert. Once you have converted an archive from A:.../Z, ExChanger will automatically list the files in A:.../Z when you choose to convert another archive. Remember that if you quit ExChanger and start it again it will use the settings it has on disk or its internal.

	To change the @{i}ExLzxTest@{ui} flag (the one that controls the testing of the Lzx archives) you will need to edit the @{i}ExLzxTestOrig@{ui} file. If you want ExChanger to test the archives it produces then you should make @{i}ExLzxTestOrig@{ui} have the "Test" word in it. If you don't want ExChanger to test the files it produces you can delete the @{i}ExLzxTestOrig@{ui} file (as ExChanger's internal setting is not to test them) or you can edit the file and type anything different from "Test" (for example "No").

	@{b}From within ExChanger:@{ub}	

	There's another way to change the files' directories. When you quit ExChanger it will ask if you want to save the directories it has in memory (@{i}ExFileInDir@{ui} and @{i}ExFileOutDir@{ui}) to disk. If you choose to do so, ExChanger will save these directories as @{i}ExFileInDirOrig@{ui} and @{i}ExFileOutDirOrig@{ui}.

	There is even another way to change the file and temporary directories. From the initial requester, you can choose 'Prefs' and then select your personal settings for those directories.
@endnode

@node Use "ExChanger - How to use"

	@{fg shine}@{b}Using ExChanger.@{ub}@{fg text}

	First of all you need to run ExChanger. To do that  you only need to double click on its @{"icon" link "Picture1/Main"}.
	Initially, ExChanger looks for the Lzx program and if it doesn't find Lzx, it will quit as Lzx is essential.
	After being started, ExChanger looks for your personal settings. Here one problem may appear. If the temporary directory choosed by you isn't empty, ExChanger presents a @{"requester" link "Picture2/Main"} asking if you want to continue. The temporary directory must be @{"empty" link Install 41} because, if not, ExChanger will archive all the files in it together with the ones from the archive you're converting, and then delete them all.
	After that you are presented with the @{"initial requester" link "Picture3/Main"}. This requester contains 5 choices: Lha, Zip, Zoo, Prefs and Quit. To begin converting choose one of the archivers, to change the settings choose 'Prefs' and to leave the script choose 'Quit'.
	If you choose to quit and ExChanger has the @{i}ExFileInDir@{ui} and @{i}ExFileOutDir@{ui} in memory it @{"asks" link "Picture9/Main"} you if you want to save them as your personal settings. If you want to save choose 'Yes'. If you don't want to save them choose 'No'.
	Next, if ExChanger has created the temporary directory Ram:ExChangerDir then it @{"asks" link "Picture4/Main"} if you want to delete the directory and all the files in it. If you want to delete them answer 'Yes'.
	If you peek 'Prefs', you are presented with a requester containing 4 choices: TempDir, FileInDir, FileOutDir and OK. To change any of the settings peek one of the first three choices. After that a file requester appears where you can select the directory to be your personal setting. To leave the requester you need to choose 'OK'.
	If you peek an archiver, you must select a file to convert. For that purpose ExChanger opens a @{"file requester" link "Picture5/Main"}.
	After choosing the archive, you have to tell ExChanger the name of the output file (.Lzx). Another @{"file requester" link "Picture6/Main"} appears to help you in the selection.
	If the output file already exists then a @{"requester" link "Picture7/Main"} appears asking if you want to continue. If you selected that file because you want to update it then select 'Yes'. If you want to create a new archiver and selected that one by mistake then select 'No' and ExChanger will restart. Do not use old archives as the output file because ExChanger will add the files from the temporary directory to that archive and you end up with a bigger archive containing lots of files from different Lha/Lzh/Zip/Zoo archives.
	If everything went alright, ExChanger has the names of the input and output files and can start the conversion.
	Then ExChanger tests the Lzx archive but only if this option is on.
	Terminated the conversion (and the testing), ExChanger @{"asks" link "Picture8/Main"} you if it should delete all the files in the temporary directory. If you want to continue converting other archives then you should choose to delete them. If you want to keep the files to check something or as a precaution, don't delete them but, please, do not continue converting because ExChanger will archive every file in the temporary directory.
	After that, ExChanger will restart and you will be presented with the @{"initial requester" link "Picture3/Main"}.
@endnode

