@node Coprigt "ExChanger - Copyright notices"

	@{b}LZX - The New Amiga Archiver
	© 1995 Data Compression Technologies@{ub}

	LZX is the state of the art archiver for the AMIGA. It has some of the most advanced features for data compression, like file merging. LZX is a co-development between Jonathan Forbes and Tomi Poutanen.


	@{b}LHA © 1991,92 Stefan Boberg@{ub}

	This archiver is the one responsible for the majority of archives in the AMIGA scene. The use of LHA is very similar to the use of LZX. Lha is fast but has a less compression ratio than LZX. It's being slowly replaced by Lzx.


	@{b}UnZip by Info-Zip
	          Portions © 1989 S.H. Smith
	          AMIGA: John Rush
	                 Paul Kienitz@{ub}

	The Zip method was developed in 1989 by S.H. Smith and has undergone some changes and developments. The most famous Zip archiver is PKZip for the MS-Dos computers.
	UnZip is a program with the main purpose of decompressing Zip archives.


	@{b}Zoo © Rahul Dhesi
	        AMIGA: J. Brian Waters@{ub}

	Zoo is an archiver developed by Rahul Dhesi and ported to the AMIGA by J. Brian Waters. It's a good archiver but now it's getting behind. It doesn't have the most @{i}up to date@{ui} data archiving technics.


	For more information about the archivers you should read the documentation that is supplied with them.



	@{b}If some of the information presented here about the archivers is wrong, I apologise in advance.@{ub}


	You can find all these archives at your favorite AMINet site in the util/arc directory.
@endnode
